snippet.textDisplay: This is wrong and sad on many levels. First, if it had been immediately made clear that absolutely all participants must be vaccinated (without the right to medical exemption), Novak would not have even gone to Australia. The judge at the first trial confirmed that he did everything that was required of him. What followed clearly showed that this was not about Djokovic, but he was suitable to be crucified as an example. He is well known enough to hear the news far and wide, and he comes from a small country that does not have enough influence to stand up for him. It’s all wrapped up in one nice story “rules are rules and they’re the same for everyone”, which in an ordinary person evokes a sense that justice has been achieved. The second trial is scandalous, because it showed that he was tried and convicted for his position on vaccination (where he did not publicly agitate anywhere to vaccinate or not vaccinate people, but only on the right to keep the vaccination status of people in private). . So he was convicted because he defended freedom of thought and the right to privacy. One thing is forgotten - the man has crossed the covid, has antibodies and a negative test for covid, so he did not endanger anyone's health. Yet he was treated as if he were a rapist, a mass murderer or a terrorist. Rules are rules and it is necessary for a society to exist and function at all, but not all rules are equally good, reasonable and fair.
